"Dairaku K., Emori S.","Dynamic and thermodynamic influences on intensified daily rainfall during the Asian summer monsoon under doubled atmospheric CO2 conditions",2006,"Geophysical Research Letters","33","1",,"","",,,10.1029/2005GL024754,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33644612852&partnerID=40&md5=a3eefa13223770863902c80ff6e0b7d8","Disaster Prevention Research Group, National Research Institute for Earth Science and Disaster Prevention, 3-1 Tennodai, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0006, Japan; Atmospheric Environment Division, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8506, Japan","Dairaku, K., Disaster Prevention Research Group, National Research Institute for Earth Science and Disaster Prevention, 3-1 Tennodai, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0006, Japan; Emori, S., Atmospheric Environment Division, National Institute for Environmental Studies, 16-2 Onogawa, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8506, Japan","Results from time-slice ensemble experiments using a T106 AGCM revealed changes in the South Asian summer monsoon resulting from climate change. Model results under global warming conditions suggested more warming over land than over the ocean, a northward shift of lower tropospheric monsoon circulation, and an increase in mean precipitation during the Asian summer monsoon. The number of extreme daily precipitation events increased significantly. Increases in mean and extreme precipitation were attributed to greater atmospheric moisture content (a thermodynamic change). In contrast, dynamic changes limited the intensification of mean precipitation. Enhanced extreme precipitation over land in South Asia arose from dynamic changes rather than thermodynamic changes. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric chemistry; Atmospheric movements; Atmospheric thermodynamics; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Mathematical models; Moisture; Rain; Atmospheric carbon dioxide conditions; Atmospheric moisture; Dailly rainfall; Lower tropospheric monsoon; Climatology; carbon dioxide enrichment; monsoon; precipitation assessment; rainfall",,,,,,"Ashrit, R.G., Douville, H., Rupa Kumar, K., Response of the Indian monsoon and ENSO-monsoon teleconnection to enhanced greenhouse effect in the CNRM coupled model (2003) J. Meteorol. Soc. Jpn., 81, pp. 779-803; Douville, H., Limitations of time-slice experiments for predicting regional climate change over South Asia (2005) Clim. Dyn., 24, pp. 373-391; Emori, S., Brown, S.J., Dynamic and thermodynamic changes in mean and extreme precipitation under changed climate (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32. , L17706, doi:10.1029/2005GL023272; Emori, S., Hasegawa, A., Suzuki, T., Dairaku, K., Validation, parameterization dependence and future projection of daily precipitation simulated with a high-resolution atmospheric GCM (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32. , L06708, doi:10.1029/2004GL022306; Goswami, B.N., Krishnamurthy, V., Annamalai, H., A broad scale circulation index for interannual variability of the Indian summer monsoon (1999) Q. J. R. Meteorol. Soc., 125, pp. 611-633; Hu, Z.-Z., Latif, M., Roeckner, E., Bengtsson, L., Intensified Asian summer monsoon and its variability in a coupled model forced by increasing greenhouse gas concentrations (2000) Geophys. Res. Lett., 27, pp. 2681-2684; Huffman, G.J., Adler, R.F., Morrissey, M.M., Bolvin, D.T., Curtis, S., Joyce, R., McGavock, B., Susskind, J., Global precipitation at one-degree daily resolution from multisatellite observations (2001) J. Hydrometeorol., 2, pp. 36-50; Inatsu, M., Kimoto, M., Difference of boreal summer climate between coupled and atmosphere-only GCMs (2005) Sci. Online Lett. Atmos., 1, pp. 105-108; Kitoh, A., Yukimoto, S., Noda, A., Motoi, T., Simulated changes in the Asian summer monsoon at times of increased atmospheric CO2 (1997) J. Meteorol. Soc. Jpn., 75, pp. 1019-1031; May, W., Simulation of the variability and extremes of daily rainfall during the Indian summer monsoon for present and futu